Hi everyone! I’m Ai-jen Poo, director of the @caringacrossgen and @domesticworkers.

Thank you for letting me take over your account, Hailey, during Women’s History Month. I’m so grateful for this chance to shine a light on our nation’s 53 million family caregivers – the nannies, house cleaners, home care workers, and family caregivers – who care for us, for our loved ones and our homes in times of crisis and stability. 

They are mostly women and predominantly Black, Latinx, and Asian women and immigrants. And do the work that makes it possible for others – especially women – to go to work. Yet the sector is defined by low wages, and few benefits. Care is essential to our society, but it is undervalued.

We’ve seen the devastating cost of not investing in care, on our grandparents, people with disabilities, and essential workers.

It might have taken a pandemic to see how childcare, paid leave and home and community care are essential infrastructure. But just like roads, bridges and broadband, all of us need care. That’s why we need YOU more than ever -- to win and build what matters most.

So I’m asking for your help to go beyond the quick fixes. If we want lasting racial and economic justice, our time is now for bold, permanent change. There is too much at stake for all of us, especially women of color. 

Go check out the stories to hear directly from care workers and caregivers.

Today is the day! I am @nseufot404, CEO of @newgeorgiaproject and I am taking over Hailey’s IG page.

Allow me to introduce myself: I’m a proud African American 🇳🇬 who goes hard for Southwest #Atlannuh.

They ask me what I do and who I do it for? The culture — I love the promise of an America of, for, and by the people, which is why I’ve dedicated the past 6 years to running #TheNewGeorgiaProject. I like to describe #NGP as a tech startup inside a civil rights organization (that’s been kicking ass btw — have you seen the news?)

I’m a gamer, aspiring sneakerhead and foodie, who has hit the pavement in 159 counties within Georgia to make sure folks are registered to #vote, confident, civically engaged, educated, and inspired.

I'm so ready to throw down with y’all, to make our democracy and Georgia better! We’re gonna keep knocking on hella doors, speaking out on the issues that matter, and going hard to close the racial voter registration gap.

I’m looking forward to having you all follow our journey @NewGeorgiaProject.

I'm @desmondmeade44, the Executive Director of @flrightsrestore, a grassroots organization dedicated to ending the disenfranchisement and discrimination against returning citizens (people with previous felony convictions). 

Did you know that before the passage of Amendment 4 in 2018, over 1.4 million Americans living in Florida were permanently banned from voting? 

Amendment 4 granted the restoration of voting rights to all returning citizens after completing their sentence, excluding convictions for murder and sexual assault.

Even after 66% of Floridians voted to pass Amendment 4, Florida's legislators ignored the will of the people, creating more financial barriers. These democracy deniers forced poor people to choose between feeding their families or paying for the right to vote. 

Where other people see obstacles, we see opportunities. Through our advocacy work in 2020, we raised more than $27 million to pay the fines and fees of over 40,000 returning citizens. 

Our work to protect voting rights is essential to the safety and improvement of our state and nation. We are an organization that believes in second chances and that every American has the power to be a change agent in their community.

Today, there are still 700,000 people who owe outstanding fines and fees and cannot participate in democracy. So, how can you join our movement? 
Follow FRRC @FlRightsRestore to get involved in our work.
Donate to our Fines and Fees Fund.
Use the hashtag #letmypeoplevote and show us how you're pledging to put people over politics.

node.text: This week we had the pleasure of meeting and speaking with @AngelaRye. As a white woman, I know I am privileged, and I didn’t always understand what that really meant. I will never understand what it’s like to be racially profiled and targeted and wake up everyday uncertain if I could lose my life because of the color of my skin. Through this conversation with Angela I really just wanted to learn, to ask questions even if I thought they were the wrong question. I want to know better so I can do better and I will not stop asking these questions and having these conversations. I want to keep learning how to be an ally, and I refuse to keep walking through life being ignorant. #BlackLivesMatter
